<p><strong>Yoga and prison have become significant parts of my life over the last few years. </p></strong>

<p>My connection to the prison system has meant teaching yoga and meditation at Salinas Valley State Prison on a weekly-ish basis, facilitating <a href="https://insight-out.org" target="_blank">GRIP</a> at Central Training Facility (Soledad), making many trips to San Quentin as well as a one memorable weekend visit to Avenal State Prison; additionally educating myself and others about the system of oppression that exists in the form of human incarceration. </p>

<p>For the independent study requirement of my 500hr advanced yoga teacher training: I produced an 8 session trauma informed introduction to yoga program for Salinas Valley State Prison, a maximum security menâ€™s correctional facility in California.  </p>

<p>My intention was to create a yoga program that was built on a foundation of <em>non harming</em>. </p>

<p>I wanted to Introduce yoga in a <strong>safe, accessible, and trauma informed</strong> way, create a <strong>healing resonance</strong>, set the foundation for a <strong> beginner practice</strong> and cultivate a sense of <strong>community and connection</strong> within the group of prisoners. </p>

<p>Each class we safely explored an element of movement, meditation, and breathwork while gradually building complexity as the sessions progressed. </p>

<p>The yoga program supported participating individuals in developing embodied awareness, healthy coping skills, and connection with oneself and others. </p>

<p>I witnessed how even with few material resources, virtually no privacy or personal space; and limited mobility it is possible to develop a yoga practice.</p>

<p>Now, I am motivated to transform this yoga program into a safe, trauma informed, and accessible introduction to yoga...book: </p>

<ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;">
<li><h3>shareable</h3></li>
<li><h3>transportable</h3></li>
<li><h3>easy to digest</h3> and, importantly</li>
<li><h4>possible to be circulated <em>back</em> into the prison system.</h4></li>
</ul>


